<br>
1. aggro really is a throwback to the lack of collisions in the game. therefore i don't really see it as skill, cuz if there were collisions, there wouldn't be skill. to those that don't know what I mean, if the game had collisions, mobs and players would actually take up physical space, and in order to get past the warrior, the mob would have to either go around him (which he could match space for space), or be forced to go through the warrior (by killing him, or maybe adding some type of grappling rules, i.e. bigger monsters would get bigger bonus's, might be able to knock down the  ). they ditched collisions because one, it requires some server cpu power (monsters making intelligent decisions on how to make pathing around players who may constantly be changing position), and two, it requires alot of bandwidth. so, I don't see aggro as a 'class worthy skill', cuz it's really stupid when you think about it that way. so open your gd eyes and see it what it is b4 u claim it as a 'skill'<br>
<br>
2. it's been mentioned before, but +100hp/mana items really screwed the pure melee classes BAD. sure, sk's/pal's are just 600hp behind, but they are also 5000 mana ahead. this wasn't a big deal when their spell list sucked, but when sk's are lining up half second dd's for 600-1200 that don't interrupt with their weapon delay, and paladins throwing around 600-1200hp heals, that 5000 is no joke. i am NOT suggesting that they get rid of good pal/sk spells or the like, i'm just saying every one of these +hp/mana items everyone gains 200+ points of stats except warriors, rogues, and monks only gained 100, and they had nothing to show for that lack of 100. they need to institute some way for warriors/rogues/monks to gain from +mana items, there are tons of ways of doing it (give them 10% of their mana for hp which you can already kinda see is how Raex is setup compared to like Grilors, have more mana actually shorten discipline reuse time, have mana increase discipline length) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 857<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/15/03 12:26:27 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: ~</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Now this is just one of hundreds of situations (both in exp groups and MOST DEFINITELY on raids) where a warrior can do what no paladin or SK can do - tank above his normal limits and do it with style, never dying, and saving the cleric mana in the process while allowing the group to achieve kills they never could have hoped to achieve without the warrior.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
