</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=brikbludgaard>Brik Bludgaard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 56<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/15/03 4:02:36 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   lets talk about spells</span><hr size=1> <br>
Lets do some spellcasting 101 for our spellcasting-impaired warrior brethren.<br>
<br>
-Even the lowliest spell costs mana... or a considerable time to refresh in the case of &quot;abilities&quot; like Harmtouch and Layhands.<br>
<br>
-Both Paladins and Shadowknights very frequently run out of mana...  and anyone who says it &quot;not a limiting factor&quot; is just proving how stupid they are.<br>
<br>
-Paladins and Shadowknights can aggro very well...  but it costs mana...  so do our heals/lifetaps, buffs/grouptaps, and everything else we cast (excepting only Layhands and Harmtouch)<br>
<br>
-Mana regens at a rate of 1 point per tick(6sec) unbuffed and with no AA's standing and at a variable rate sitting depending on meditation skill...  but meditation is a pointless endeavor as Pal/SK never sit during combat, and rarely get to sit between pulls.  Spells such as KEI and similar spells increase mana regen... but no matter HOW much mana regen a Pal/SK gets from spells/AA, it has never allowed me to cast at will and play more than one role well or two roles less well...  I always have time when I must refrain from casting or have no reserve.<br>
<br>
-Knights use their spells to actually be more than nerfed warrior.  When the mana is gone, the knight is a warrior with lower skillcaps and terrible disciplines, and lesser equipment...  a class no one would want to play.<br>
<br>
-Knights with mana can do some very nice things, and for a short time can use their spells to exceed warriors in one or two areas.<br>
For example, as a shadowknight, I can:<br>
*Feign Death<br>
*Throw nukes/lifetaps between swings to exceed warrior melee damage.<br>
*Make myself a better tank by trying to channel a lifetap or defenisive spell through a mob beating on me (the likelyhood of channeling a spell through is not very good when large amounts of damage are being done to me....)<br>
*increase my party's damage output with ATK taps.<br>
*buff myself to some degree (most of my spells are overwritten by standard group fare however)<br>
*Garner aggro quickly<br>
*KEEP aggro despite other factor<br>
<br>
Note that spells like lifetaps do actually two things at once, both healing and increasing my damage...  but they also cost huge amounts of mana.<br>
<br>
Note, that I can only do a limited amount of those things, AND for a limited time before going OOM.<br>
<br>
I can do some of them at a less-efficient rate to try to keep some mana.. but then I am not going to be better than a warrior anywhere.<br>
<br>
-ALL spellcasters are limited to 8 spell slots at once...  Shadowknights must choose a set of spells to use for each party they are in...  usually chosen by role the group asks them to take.  Yes, we can sit and mem spells, but the fact that memming spells in combat is to say the least difficult... (especially for the SK who is usually puller or tank)<br>
<br>
-The tradeoff is that a warrior can do EVERYTHING they are all the time...  (with the exception of disciplines)  and the combo of more HP, easier attainable better equipment, and better skillcaps....<br>
<br>
<br>
-Lets try an example:<br>
I am tanking for a group, and I choose to go heavy on the taunt spells...  I can maintain aggro and even get it back should I lose it....  but I will be able to throw VERY little in the way of damage spells or lifetaps and actually have the mana to continue my lock on aggro...  IN most cases  most of my damage spells are passed over in favor of spells that do more aggro and less damage.  I load a few lifetaps, but know that throwing them will guarantee the fact I will be OOM in just a few of them. <br>
<br>
I am then asked to pull AND tank...  Due to the mana lost in Feign pulls and the absolute lack of ANY med time at all, I can no longer throw any spells designed for damaghe outside of my aggro spells, and in addition, I can no longer assure the fact aggro is locked anymore...  I CAN outaggro a warrior, but my mana is being stetched...  I am also doing less melee damage overall as I cannot maintain my ATK spells and pull and keep aggro...  If I throw any lifetaps at ALL, I will be OOM in short order...  we WILL have downtime.<br>
<br>
Then we grab a warrior... I am now pulling and can put away my aggro spells (except for voice which I cast on the warrior) I now take more damage spells that confer less aggro and that allow me to deal efficient damage/mana point....<br>
<br>
We get a monk,  and I ask him to pull...  I load up on damage and bardlike spells that aid the party with some bodyguard-like spells in order to grab aggro quickly (mana inefficient, but great for quick grabs)<br>
<br>
ALL of this was with VoQ and as many mana-regen spells as I could find.<br>
<br>
Mana IS a limiting factor....  if you don't know this, then you are VERY misinformed.<br>
<br>
Hybrids use their spells as an addition to their WHOLE...<br>
its not like warriors where every spell cast on you or that you cast yourself is a bonus...  our spells are an integral part of our balance...<br>
<br>
It seems many warriors are misled about mana... thinking its as infinite as their own abilities...  you couldn't be more wrong.<br>
<br>
The grass is not greener...  do some reading please...  nearly EVERY other class claims &quot;I cannot get groups&quot; and &quot;I am broken&quot; and its usually the 60th+ level newbies who are being turned down due to their obvious ebay-ness, (say for those of you who STILL don't know how taunt works) not due to their class weaknesses.<br>
<br>
Warriors DO have issues... this much I and most experienced hybrids will agree with... and aggro is one of them...  I would love to see warriors have some additional ability to add numerical hate that isnt linked to the taunt button. (say perhaps KICK)<br>
<br>
I would love to see experienced warrior and hybrids form a balanced solution...  a little work and some reality checks from both sides would be both fun and interesting...  and it wouldn't be the first time such suggestions were integrated into the game.<br>
<br>
End the exaggeration please...  end the stupid grass is greener...  learn a bit about hybrids before embarassing yourself please.<br>
<br>
Brik <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=glatius2>Glatius2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>will kick your @$$</span><br>  Posts: 858<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/15/03 5:13:44 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: lets talk about spells</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Mana IS a limiting factor.... if you don't know this, then you are VERY misinformed.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Given the mana cost reductions due to AAXP and items and additional mana regen provided other spells such as KEI and the fact that more and more items have mana as one of their stats, mana is far from the limiting factor it once was.  To claim that a knight of any kind can't continue to provide substantially greater aggro control for a prolonged period without running oom is untrue.  If I have a Paladin telling me with authority that all he typically needs is two stuns per battle, are you seriously trying to convince me that every 10-15 minutes you have to be oom?<br>
<br>
Besides, if I can watch a Shadow Knight lock aggro through all the waves of the executioner's trial and still have mana at the end, while the Wizard and Cleric are both oom, it seems that the Knight's mana won't really be the issue.<br>
<br>
And on top of that, I've grouped with Knights who have tanked for hours and the only time they medded for any length of time was when someone needed an afk break or when someone else requested the break for mana.<br>
<br>
No, you can't dot your heart out.  No the Paladin can't heal two or three times every battle.  Yes, you have to use some common sense and hold back a reserve.  But no, you're not mana starved all the time.  Besides, even if you have to hold back on damage output to reserve mana while tanking, your group can open up more on their damage output.  You'll get more damage from 3 DPS classes going full bore than you will from just the damage you could do if you weren't tanking.  So that whole, well I lose DPS, arguement is extremely weak.  When tanking a knight's DPS is almost irrelevant as long as they hold aggro well enough to allow everyone else to do their damage at full or close to full potential.    <br>
<br>
Yes mana is a restriction.  No, mana isn't as big a restriction as it once was and some people would like us to continue to believe.  But hey, thanks for coming over to school us because we don't understand the game. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :rolleyes --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/eyes.gif ALT=":rolleyes"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
